\section{Introduction}\label{sec1}

In the last decade, a large experimental progress in the charmed-strange meson spectrum has archived. Some radially or orbitally excited charmed-strange mesons have been observed \cite{Agashe:2014kda}, which not only makes the charmed-strange meson family lengthy, but also raises some challenges to the conventional quark model \cite{Godfrey:1985xj}. Among these newly observed charmed-strange mesons, the $D_{s0}^{\ast}(2317)$ and the $D_{s1}(2460)$ are two particular states, since their masses are far below the quark model expectations \cite{Godfrey:1985xj}.


The observations of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ was firstly reported by the {\it BABAR} Collaboration in the $D_s^+ \pi^0$ invariant mass spectrum of the $B$ decay process and the mass of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ was measured to be $(2316.8 \pm 0.4)$ MeV \cite{Aubert:2003fg}. Later, the CLEO Collaboration confirmed the existence of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and further reported another structure $D_{s1}(2460)$ in the $D_s^{\ast +} \pi^0 $ invariant mass distribution, the mass difference of the $D_{s1}(2460)$ and the $D_{s}^\ast$ was fitted to be $351.2 \pm 1.7 (\mathrm{stat}.) \pm 1.0 (\mathrm{syst}.)$ MeV~\cite{Besson:2003cp}. Besides the $D_s^\ast \pi^0$ mode, some other decay modes of the $D_{s1}(2460)$, like $D_s \gamma$, $D_s^{\ast} \gamma$, $D_{s} \pi^+ \pi^-$ and $D_{s0}^\ast \gamma $ had also been measured~\cite{Besson:2003cp}.


After the observations from the {\it BABAR} and CLEO Collaborations \cite{Aubert:2003fg, Besson:2003cp}, the existences of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ had been confirmed by the Belle Collaboration \cite{Abe:2003jk, Krokovny:2003zq} and {\it BABAR} Collaboration itself \cite{Aubert:2004pw, Aubert:2003pe, Aubert:2006bk}. And now, the particle data group (PDG) averages of the masses of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ are \cite{Agashe:2014kda},
\begin{eqnarray}
m_{D_{s0}^\ast}(2317)&=& (2317.7 \pm 0.6)\ \mathrm{MeV}, \nonumber\\
m_{D_{s1}}(2460)&=&(2459.5 \pm 0.6)\  \mathrm{MeV},\nonumber
\end{eqnarray}
respectively. In addition, the decay mode of $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma$ had been measured by the CLEO and {\it BABAR} Collaborations \cite{Besson:2003cp, Aubert:2003pe} and  the ratio of $\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to  D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma ) $ and $ \Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D^\ast \pi^0)$ were reported to be,
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to  D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma )}{ \Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D_s^\ast \pi^0)}
\left\{
  \begin{array}{ll}
    <0.58, & \hbox{CLEO \cite{Besson:2003cp},} \\
    <0.22, & \hbox{{\it BABAR} \cite{Aubert:2003pe},}
  \end{array}
\right.
\label{Eq:ratio}
\end{eqnarray}
at the $90 \%$ confidence level.

Theoretically, the quark model predicted masses of the $D_{s0}^\ast$ and $D_{s1}$ are 2480 MeV and $2530$~MeV \cite{Godfrey:1985xj}, which are about $160$~MeV and $70$~MeV, respectively, above the experimental measured values. This disagreement between the quark model prediction and experimental measurement makes people think that these two states unlike conventional charmed-strange mesons.


The particular properties of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ stimulate the theorist interests in the natures of these two states. The large $N_c$ expansion calculations also indicated that the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ could not be a standard quark-antiquark meson~\cite{Guo:2015dha}. The mass and decay modes of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ was considered in the  $c\bar{s}q\bar{q}$ tetra-quark frame \cite{Nielsen:2007zz, Nielsen:2005zr, Terasaki:2003qa}. The QCD sum rule calculations also supported that the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ could be a tetraquark state \cite{Wang:2006uba, Bracco:2005kt}. However, the couple channel estimations indicated that $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ could be $P-$wave charmed-strange mesons with strong coupling to $DK$ and $D^\ast K$ \cite{Lutz:2008zz, Hwang:2004cd}. With some fine tuning paramters, the masses of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ could be reproduced in a relativistic quark model \cite{Liu:2013maa}. In Ref. \cite{Wang:2006mf}, the radiative decays of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ were estimated with vector-mesons-dominance in the QCD sum rule frame, in which the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ were assigned as $P-$wave charmed strange mesons. The isospin violating decays of these two states were evaluated in the chiral effective theory since the pion emitted from $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ were rather soft \cite{Fajfer:2015zma}. These two states were also studied by QCD sum rule in heavy quark effective theory in a conventional charmed-strange meson picture \cite{Dai:2003yg}.

It should be noticed that the masses of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ are about 40 MeV below the thresholds of the $D K$ and $D^\ast K$, respectively, which naturally indicates that the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ could be good candidates of the $DK$ and $D^\ast K$ hadronic molecules. The $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ had been analyzed in the $DK$ hadronic molecule picture by Beth-Salpeter approach \cite{Xie:2010zza}. The $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ were considered as a kaonic molecules bound by hard core attraction in Ref. \cite{Bicudo:2004dx}. The decay behaviors of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ were extensively investigated in $DK$ and $D^\ast K $ hadronic molecule scenario \cite{Faessler:2007gv, Faessler:2007us, Cleven:2014oka}, and the productions of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ from the nonleptonic $B$ decay were calculated in Ref.~\cite{Datta:2003re}, in which $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ were considered as hadronic molecule states of $DK$ and $D^\ast K$, respectively .


In this paper, we study the radiative and pionic transitions from the $D_{s1}(2460)$ to the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ in the hadronic molecular interpretation. With the assignment that the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ are the hadronic molecule states of $DK$ and $D^\ast K$, respectively, one could find that the radiative and pionic transitions from the $D_{s1}(2460)$ to the $D_{s0}^\ast (2317)$ occur via the subprocesses $D^\ast \to D\gamma$ and $D^\ast \to D \pi^0$, respectively. As for the $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \pi^0$, it is an isospin violated decay mode, which could resulted from the masses differences of charged and neutral $D$ and $K$ mesons and $\eta-\pi^0$ mixing. 
In addition, the decay mode of $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma$ had been measured by the CLEO and {\it BABAR} Collaborations \cite{Besson:2003cp, Aubert:2003pe}. In the present work, we also estimate the partial width for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D^\ast  \pi^0$ to further test the $D^\ast K$ assignment of the $D_{s1}(2460)$ by comparing the estimated ratio of $\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to  D_{s0}(2317) \gamma )$ and $\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D^\ast \pi^0)$ with the experimental measured one.

This work is organized as follows: the structures of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ are discussed in the hadronic molecule scenario in Section \ref{Sec2}. The partial widths for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \pi^0,\ \ D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma, \ \ D_s^\ast \pi^0$ are estimated in Section \ref{Sec3}. The numerical results for the partial widths of the $D_{s1}(2460)$ are present in Section \ref{sec4} and Section \ref{sec5} is dedicated to a short summary.


\section{Hadronic molecule structures of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$}\label{Sec2}

In the hadronic molecule scenario, the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ are assigned as $S-$wave $DK$ and $D^\ast K$ molecule states, respectively. Here, we adopt the effective Lagrangians to describe the interactions of the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ and $D_{s1}(2460)$ and their components, the concrete form the Lagrangians are \cite{Faessler:2007gv,Faessler:2007us}
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq:s0dk}
