$K^{(\ast )\dagger}=(K^{(\ast )-},\bar K^{(\ast )0}), D^{(\ast )\dagger}=(\bar D^{(\ast )0},D^{(\ast )-})$.

In the heavy quark effective theory, the coupling $D^\ast D^{(\ast)} P$ could relate to gauging coupling constant $g$ via,
\begin{eqnarray}
g_{D^\ast D^\ast P}=\frac{2g}{f_{\pi}}\,,\quad g_{D^\ast DP}=\frac{2g}{f_{\pi}}\sqrt{m_{D^\ast }m_D}\,,
\end{eqnarray}
where $f_{\pi}=132$\,MeV is the decay constant of pion and the gauge coupling $g=0.59$ is estimated by the experimental value of the partial width for the $D^{\ast+} \to D^+ \pi^0$. The involved coupling constants between $K^\ast$ and the charmed or charmed-strange mesons are \cite{Oh:2000qr},
\begin{eqnarray}
g_{D_s^\ast D^\ast K^\ast}=\frac{\beta g_V}{\sqrt{2}}, \ \ \ f_{D_s^\ast D^\ast V} =\frac{\lambda g_V}{\sqrt{2}} \sqrt{m_{D_s^\ast D^\ast}},
\end{eqnarray}
where the gauge coupling $\beta=0.9$, $\lambda=0.56$ and $g_V=m_\rho/f_\pi$.







As for the coupling constants of $g_{K^\ast K \pi}$ and $g_{K^\ast K \eta}$, we adopt $g_{K^\ast K \pi}=3.21$ and $g_{K^\ast K \eta}=4.47$, which are evaluated by $SU(3)$ symmetry \cite{Liu:2005jb}.

The involved interaction related to the photon field and the charmed mesons is in the form \cite{Chen:2010re},
\begin{eqnarray}
&&\mathcal{L}_{D^\ast D\gamma}=\bigg\{\frac{g_{D^{\ast +}D^+\gamma}}{4}e\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}F_{\mu\nu}D^{\ast +}_{\alpha\beta}D^-\nonumber\\                         &&\phantom{\mathcal{L}_{D^\ast D\gamma}=}+\frac{g_{D^{\ast 0}D^0\gamma}}{4}e\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}F_{\mu\nu}D^{\ast 0}_{\alpha\beta}\bar D^0\bigg\}+h.c.\,,
\end{eqnarray}
where strength tensors are defined as $F_{\mu\nu}= \partial_{\mu}A_{\nu} -\partial_{\nu}A_{\mu},\  D^\ast _{\alpha \beta} =\partial_{\alpha}D^\ast _{\beta} -\partial_{\beta}D^\ast _{\alpha}$. The coupling of $g_{D^{\ast+} D^+ \gamma }=-0.5 \ \mathrm{GeV}^{-1}$ is estimated from the partial width of $D^{\ast +} \to D^+ \gamma$, the minus sign is adopt according to the Lattice QCD and QCD sum rule calculations  \cite{Becirevic:2009xp,Zhu:1996qy}. As for $g_{D^{\ast0} D^0 \gamma}$, only the branching ratios of $ D^{\ast0} \to D^0 \gamma  $ and $D^{\ast0} \to D^0 \pi^0 $ are measured. Here, we can roughly estimate the partial width of $D^{\ast0} \to D^0 \pi^0$ from the one of $D^{\ast +} \to D^+ \pi^0$ via isospin symmetry \cite{Dong:2008gb, Chen:2015igx}. With the measured ratio of $\Gamma(D^{\ast0} \to D^0 \gamma)$ and $\Gamma(D^{\ast0} \to D^0 \pi^0)$, we can obtain the partial width of $D^{\ast0}\to D^0 \gamma$, and the corresponding coupling constant, $g_{D^{\ast 0} D^0 \gamma}$, which is $g_{D^{\ast 0} D^0 \gamma} =2.0\ \mathrm{GeV}^{-1}$.


