The partial width of $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast (2317)\pi^0$ is present in Fig.~\ref{fig:n-s0-pi}. In the present calculation, we varies the $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ from 1.0 to 2.0 GeV and take several typical values of $\Lambda_{D_{s0}^\ast}$, which are $1.0$, $1.5$ and 2.0 GeV, respectively. Our calculation indicates that the partial width of $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast (2317)\pi^0$ is of order 0.1 keV, which is rather small since the phase space of this process is very limit. In addition, this partial width weakly depend on the parameter $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ and $\Lambda_{D_{s0}^\ast}$, and decreases with the increasing of $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ or $\Lambda_{D_{s0}^\ast}$. In particular, for the case of $\Lambda_{D_{s0}^\ast}=1.0$ GeV, the partial width for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast (2317)\pi^0$ decrease from $0.25$ to $0.21$ keV with $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ increasing from 1.0 to 2 GeV. In the molecule scenario, the partial width for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast (2317)\pi^0$ is predicted to be about $0.19 \sim 0.25$ keV in the considered parameters range.

