As for the radiative transition from the $D_{s1}(2460)$ to the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$, the $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ dependence of the partial width is present in Fig. \ref{fig:n-s0-ga}. Similar to the case of pionic transition from the $D_{s1}(2460)$ to the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$, the partial width for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma$ also weakly depend on the parameter $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ and $\Lambda_{D_{s0}^\ast}$. In the considered parameters range, the partial width for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma$ varies from  $2.96$ to $3.13$ keV. The PDG average of the branching ratio for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma$ is $3.7_{-2.4}^{+5.0} \%$, however, the width of $D_{s1}(2460)$ is not well determined, one cannot compared the theoretical estimated partial width with the experimental measurement. Here, we also notice that both widths for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \pi^0$ and $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma$ weakly depend on the model parameters, and the former one is about one order smaller than the latter one, which indicates that the branching ratio of $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \pi^0$ should be of order $10^{-3}$.


\begin{figure}[htb]
\includegraphics[scale=0.75]{dsstarpi.eps}
\caption{The $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ dependence of the partial width for $D_{s1}(2460)\to D^{\ast }_s\pi^0$. \label{fig:n-s1-sstar}}.
\end{figure}

In Fig. \ref{fig:n-s1-sstar}, we present the $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ dependences of the partial width for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s}^{\ast} \pi^0$. The partial width $\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D_s^\ast \pi^0)$ increases with the increasing of $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$, in particular, the partial width varies from 32 keV to 46 keV with $\Lambda_{D_{s1}}$ increasing from 1 to 2 GeV, which is much larger than partial widths for $D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma$ and $D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \pi^0$ modes. In addition, in the present work, the partial widths for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma$ and $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s}^\ast \pi^0$ have been estimated in the molecule scenario, and the ratio of $\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^\ast(2317) \gamma)$ and $\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s}^\ast \pi^0)$ is estimated to be $(6.6\sim10.2)\times 10^{-2}$ in the considered paramters range, which is safely under the upper limit reported by the CLEO and{\it BABAR} Collaborations \cite{Besson:2003cp, Aubert:2003pe}.

\section{Summary} \label{sec5}

In the present work, we estimate the partial widths for the radiative and pionic transitions from the $D_{s1}(2460)$ to the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ in a molecule scenario, in which the $D_{s1}(2460)$ and the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$ are assigned as a $DK$ and a $D^\ast K$ molecule state, respectively. To further test the molecule interpretations to the $D_{s1}(2460)$ and the $D_{s0}^\ast(2317)$, we also calculate the partial width for $D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s}^\ast \pi^0$. In the considered parameters range, the discussed partial widths are evaluated to be,
\begin{eqnarray}
\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460)\to D^{\ast }_{s0}(2317)\pi^0)&=& 0.19\sim 0.22\,\text{keV},\nonumber\\
\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460)\to D^{\ast }_{s0}(2317)\gamma)&=&3.0 \sim 3.1\,\text{keV},\nonumber\\
\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460)\to D^{\ast }_s\,\pi^0) &=&31.3 \sim 45.2\,\text{keV}.
\end{eqnarray}

Our estimations indicate that the partial width for the $D_{s1}(2460)\to D^{\ast }_{s0}(2317)\pi^0$ is about one order smaller than the one of $D_{s1}(2460)\to D^{\ast }_{s0}(2317)\gamma$. The branching ratio for $D_{s1}(2460)\to D^{\ast }_{s0}(2317)\gamma$ is measured to be $3.7 _{-2.4}^{+5.0}\%$ \cite{Agashe:2014kda}, thus the branching ratio for $D_{s1}(2460)\to D^{\ast }_{s0}(2317)\pi^0$ is roughly determined to be of order $10^{-3}$.
In addition, we further estimate the ratio of ${\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^{\ast }(2317)\gamma)}$ and ${\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D_s^{\ast +}\,\pi^0)}$ to be,
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D_{s0}^{\ast }(2317)\gamma)}{\Gamma(D_{s1}(2460) \to D_s^{\ast +}\,\pi^0)}=(6.6-10.6)\times 10^{-2},
\end{eqnarray}
which is consistent with the experimental measurements from the CLEO and {\it BABAR} Collaborations \cite{Besson:2003cp, Aubert:2003pe}.

At present, the experimental information of the $D_{s1}(2460)$ and $D_{s0}(2317)$ is not abundant at present, especially the widths of these states are not well measured. The measurements of their decay behaviors in LHCb and forthcoming Belle II could provide further test to the results in the present work.



